(2) understand managerial decision-making processes;
(3) understand various algorithms of data mining;
(4) develop self-learning in the area beyond the topics covered by this course;
(5) provide hands on experience by using data mining application (e.g. SAS Enterprise Miner);
(6) know how to apply the data mining application to solve the real problems.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
(1) master important economic relationships that determine success in a business environment;
(2) make use of a number of tools, including decision tree analysis, value-added analysis, five-force analysis, competitive market analysis and game-theoretic analysis, in addressing strategic and decision problems;
(3) use Excel to incorporate data into an analytical framework;
(4) explore implications and limitations from the analytical framework;
(5) communicate and interact with non-specialists to discuss the issues involved and the pros and cons of a prescribed decisions from the analysis.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
(1) understand that risk and operations management plays a critical role in a business and how it contributes to the success of the business;
(2) utilize quantitative tools, including linear, integer, and non-linear programming, regression, statistical analysis, and simulation, to model and analyze business problems;
(3) derive key trade-offs involved in managing business operations with the aid of data and analytics;
(4) speak the language of risk and operations management in communicating and interacting with non-specialists and discussing related issues.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
(1) master the techniques and tools to track, collect, measure, report, and analyze quantitative Internet data to optimize websites and web marketing initiatives;
(2) design strategies to optimize web operation and improve online performance;
(3) apply web analytics skills and practices to solve business problems, enhance business decisions, and improve business intelligence; and
(4) align web strategy to organizational IT and business strategies for business performance and competitiveness.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
